{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A file placed inside a subdirectory of the watched root is processed, not only files placed directly in the root directory.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The failure boundary is real filesystem watch recursion across OS event delivery. A mock watcher can report subdirectory events even if real recursive watching is misconfigured, so MOCK-MISS and REAL-INFRA both apply.","test_description":"Start the daemon against a temp watched root and temp output dir. Create a nested subdirectory under the watched root, write a new file into it, and assert the transformed output appears once in output without restarting the daemon.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.78,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The deduplication logic correctly discards a second processing request for the same file path within a configurable time window.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is mostly deterministic logic, but real failures are often at module wiring boundaries (path normalization + dedup cache + scheduler/queue). A pure unit test of just one function can miss those interactions; no OS/network/LLM dependency is required.","test_description":"Wire the real intake->dedup->process path in-process with a fake clock or controllable time source. Submit the same file path twice inside the dedup window and assert only one pipeline execution; then advance time past the window and assert a new request is accepted.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When the operating system emits multiple filesystem events for a single file write, the daemon processes the file exactly once.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Correctness depends on real OS watcher event patterns (duplicate/rapid event bursts). Mocked event streams can hide real duplication timing and ordering, so REAL-INFRA and MOCK-HIDE apply.","test_description":"Run the daemon with a real temp directory and perform a single file write pattern known to emit multiple events on the host OS (e.g., write+rename or chunked write). Assert exactly one completed transformation for that file path.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.86,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"If the watched directory is removed and then recreated while the daemon is running, the daemon resumes watching the new directory without a restart.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is OS/filesystem lifecycle behavior (watch handle invalidation and re-subscription). In-process mocks usually do not reproduce watcher teardown/recreate edge cases, so real infra is needed.","test_description":"Start daemon on a real temp watched directory. Remove the directory while daemon is live, recreate it at the same path, then add a new file. Assert the new file is processed without daemon restart.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.91,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When multiple files arrive at the same time, they are processed in the order determined by their creation timestamps.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The critical boundary is ordering logic across queueing + metadata lookup modules. This can be validated without external services, though a pure unit test of sorter logic may miss intake/queue wiring mistakes. OS-level timestamp quirks are relevant but not strictly required for the minimum viable failure-catching test.","test_description":"Use real intake and queue modules with a temp filesystem fixture. Create multiple files in quick succession with controlled timestamp metadata (or explicit metadata injection path used by production code), trigger intake, and assert processing order matches creation timestamps.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.17,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"A file that is still being written to when the arrival event fires is not picked up for processing until writing is complete.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This depends on real write-in-progress timing and OS event semantics. Mocked dependencies often hide race conditions where partial files are consumed too early, so REAL-INFRA and MOCK-HIDE apply.","test_description":"Start daemon on a real temp watched directory. Begin writing a large file in chunks with delays so arrival event occurs before final chunk/close. Assert no processing starts before write completion, then assert exactly one successful processing after close.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.89,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}}]}
